Docker:
  Docker operates on a Client-Server architecture that leverages low-level Linux kernel features to provide isolation.
  Instead of hardware virtualization (like a VM), Docker uses OS-level virtualization, making it significantly faster and more lightweight.

1. The High-Level Architecture
  Docker is split into three main components that communicate via a REST API:
      The Client: This is where you type commands (e.g., docker run). 
                It acts as the user interface and sends your instructions to the Daemon.
      The Daemon (dockerd): The "brain" of Docker. 
                It runs in the background on the Host machine and manages images, containers, networks, and volumes.
      The Registry: A store for Docker Images. 
                Docker Hub is the default public registry, but you can also have private ones.

2. How it works "Under the Hood"
    Docker isn't magic; it uses two specific features of the Linux Kernel to create the "bubble" that is a container:
    A. Namespaces (Isolation)
        Namespaces provide the isolation layer. 
        They make the container think it has its own dedicated resources, even though it's sharing the host's kernel.
            PID Namespace: Provides isolated process IDs (Process #1 inside the container is not Process #1 on your laptop).
            Net Namespace: Gives the container its own network stack (IP addresses, routing tables).
            Mnt Namespace: Isolates filesystem mount points (The container has its own root /).
    B. Control Groups / cgroups (Resource Limits)
        While namespaces provide isolation, cgroups provide limitations. 
        They ensure a single container doesn't "hog" all the RAM or CPU of the host machine. 
        You can tell a container: "You are only allowed to use 512MB of RAM."

3. The Lifecycle of a docker run Command
    When you type docker run hello-world, the following chain reaction occurs:
        Client sends a request to the Daemon.
        Daemon checks if the hello-world Image exists locally.
        If not, the Daemon Pulls it from the Registry (Docker Hub).
        The Daemon creates a Container from that image (like a class instance from a blueprint).
        The Daemon allocates a read-write layer on top of the read-only image layers.
        The Daemon creates a network interface and assigns an IP.
        The application inside the container executes.

4. Layered File System (UnionFS)
      Docker images are built in layers. 
      Each instruction in a Dockerfile (like RUN apt-get install) creates a new layer.
        Read-Only Layers: All layers of an image are immutable.
        Copy-on-Write: When a container is running and you modify a file, Docker copies that file to the top "Container Layer" (Read-Write) and modifies it there. 
            This makes image sharing extremely efficient because multiple containers can share the same base image layers.

Feature       Docker (Container)            Virtual Machine (VM)
Architecture  Shares the Host OS Kernel.    Includes a full Guest OS.
Size          Megabytes (Very Small).       Gigabytes (Large).
Startup Time  Milliseconds.                 Minutes.
Efficiency    High (Low overhead).          Lower (High hardware emulation).

Feature	            Application Logs	                      Kubectl Logs
Who creates it?	    Your code / Logic.	                    The Kubernetes API / Container Runtime.
Where is it stored?	Disk, Console, or Remote Log Server.	  Local disk of the Worker Node.
What does it show?	Whatever the dev decided to log.	      Only the stdout and stderr streams.
Visibility	        Requires access to the file/stream.	    Requires RBAC permissions to the K8s cluster.
Command	            tail -f app.log (on a server).         	kubectl logs <pod-name>.

The "Golden Rule" for Kubernetes:
  To make your application logs visible via kubectl logs, you must follow the Twelve-Factor App principle: Treat logs as event streams. 
  Instead of writing to files inside the container, configure your app to write everything to the console (System.out in Java, console.log in Node, etc.). 
  This allows Kubernetes to capture the data and allows tools like Fluentd or Splunk to easily scrape them for long-term storage.

  Pro Tip: If your app is stuck writing to a file and you can't change the code, you can use a Sidecar Pattern.
  A small second container runs in the same Pod, reads your log file, and pipes it to stdout so that kubectl logs works again.
